Citations
Date: 0/0/1941
Source: NZ Slang
Author: BAKER
Vol / Page: /57
Edition:
Quote: <i>Surf-hurdling</i> seems to be ... New Zealand ... though there is reason to suspect it is used extensively in the Pacific. It describes the practice of landing goods from a ship to shore in an open boat on an exposed coastlne. The taking of goods, especially wool, from shore to ship in an open boat is also termed <i>surf-hurdling</i>.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1946
Source: New Zealand: Pacific Pioneer
Author: SOLJAK
Vol / Page: 118
Edition:
Quote:  New Zealanders have coined or adapted many expressions to meet local requirements, as illustrated by the following: ... <i>surf hurdling</i>: landing goods from ship to shore, or vice versa, in an open boat
